channel.title: First Ever Model
channel.description:
So me and a friend of mine decided we were gonna start working on our own Runescape Private server, he referred me to Metasequoia and I had a little play around. I wanted to just get some opinions on this model i made, see what you guys think. I'm not yet sure if i can put it into RS somehow, but it was mainly to get the hang of Meta. [img]http://i913.photobucket.com/albums/ac333/roamonline/Models/Wingsfinal4.jpg[/img] [img]http://i913.photobucket.com/albums/ac333/roamonline/Models/Wingsfinal3.jpg[/img] [img]http://i913.photobucket.com/albums/ac333/roamonline/Models/Wingsfinal2.jpg[/img] [img]http://i913.photobucket.com/albums/ac333/roamonline/Models/Wingsfinal1.jpg[/img]
Remember this my first ever model, please go easy on me :( I know that the back of them is very messy, mainly because i was silly and forgot it until last.

item.title: First Ever Model
item.dc:creator: @lewigi lewigi
item.description:
@lewigi wrote:

[quote=“man_killerx, post:14, topic:328640”]Well it looks like you just threw a whole bunch of primitives together, Here are some tips. Get a reference image and work off of it. Try trace modeling, This will eventually lead into freehand modeling witch is actually fun to do. But try making simple shapes. A cylinder with a ball on the end (This can make a hilt). Make a square, Then stretch the sides to make a blade (This can make a blade…) Then join the two together to make a simple sword. Now that you have mastered the basic’s of prim’s. Time to get into detail, Try to menipulate the primitive by adding section to move around. This can really be usefull in the future, But do not try to keep using the same method of modeling because after a while you’re models will grow old.

Here is a list of models you can make to get you started,

A sword.
A shield.
A NPC (okay not that yet).

I look forward to seeing models from you.[/quote]
Thank you, this is exactly what i needed to know. (Just for the record, i didn’t use one primitive). I did sketch this wing and scan it in, and modelled from it, but your right, i should have started learning with primitives, and not such a complicated model. I will start to try and make some simple swords and small items, rather than jumping in the deep end. Thanks again

Read full topic
